Duck typing is a design pattern in which objects are treated as having certain properties or methods based on their behavior, rather than their explicit type. In other words, if an object "quacks like a duck" (acts like a duck), it is treated as a duck, regardless of its actual type. This is often used in dynamic languages like Python and JavaScript, where types are not explicitly declared.

So, in TypeScript, you can use duck typing by creating an interface that defines the properties or methods that an object must have in order to be considered of that type. For example:

```
interface Quackable {
  quack(): void;
}

class Duck implements Quackable {
  quack(): void {
    console.log("Quack!");
  }
}

class RubberDuck implements Quackable {
  quack(): void {
    console.log("Squack!");
  }
}

function quack(duck: Quackable): void {
  duck.quack();
}

const duck: Quackable = new Duck();
const rubberDuck: Quackable = new RubberDuck();

quack(duck); // Quack!
quack(rubberDuck); // Squack!
```


In this example, we create an interface called Quackable that defines the quack() method that all objects that implement this interface must have. We then create two classes, Duck and RubberDuck, that implement this interface by defining their own implementations of the quack() method. Finally, we create a function called quack() that takes a parameter of type Quackable and calls its quack() method. When we call this function with both a Duck and a RubberDuck object, it behaves correctly because they both implement the Quackable interface, even though they are different classes with different implementations of the quack() method. This is an example of duck typing in TypeScript.

